ities of the state. Manipulation is explored in relation to the Coalition Government and the exploitation of the Liberal Democrats, on policies such as austerity, tuition fees and electoral reform. Finally, the book examines Cameronism in relation to current challenges to the existing political order: Brexit, Scottish independence, and the rise of populism. This timely book is essential reading to those interested in British party politics and Prime Ministerial leadership.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 4aPolitical Studies 2020. 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / History & Theory.2bisacsh  aAusterity.  aBrexit.  aBritish government 2010-16.  aCameronism.  aConservatism.  aDavid Cameron.  aPolitical manipulation.  aPolitical modernisation.  aThatcherism.  aThe Conservative Party.1 aHeppell, Timothy, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertManchester University Press 2020 eBook-Packagez978311128248040uhttps://doi.org/10.7765/978152611630740uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781526116307423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781526116307/original  a978-3-11-128248-0  Manchester University Press 2020 eBook-Packageb2020  aGBV-deGruyter-alles